servings: 2
---

Adjust rack to middle position (top and middle positions for 4 servings) and preheat oven to low broil. Wash and dry produce.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @onion{1}.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a #medium pan{}, preferably nonstick, over medium-high heat. Add onion; cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and softened, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Add @sugar{1%tsp} (2 tsp for 4 servings) and a splash of @water{}; cook, stirring occasionally, until caramelized, ~{2-3%minutes} more. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> TIP: If you added any other items to your meal (apps, sides, and/or desserts), you can get started on them now!

Meanwhile, trim, peel, and cut @carrots{6%ounce} into sticks (like fries; ours were 3 inches long and 1/3 inch thick). Core, deseed, and dice half the @long green pepper{1} into 1⁄4-inch pieces; cut remaining green pepper into 1⁄4-inch strips.

In a #medium bowl{}, combine @marinara sauce{5%ounce} and half the @garlic powder{2%tsp} (reserve remaining garlic powder for serving). Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Place @pita bread{4} on a lightly oiled #baking sheet{} (divide between two baking sheets for 4 servings). Evenly spread sauce over pitas.

Place @mozzarella cheese{1%cup}, diced green pepper, caramelized onion, and @pepperoni{3.5%ounce} in separate serving vessels. Arrange sauce-topped pitas and toppings family style for everyone to build their own pitzas. (You'll broil the pitzas in the next step!)

Broil pitzas on middle rack until cheese melts and edges are golden brown, ~{4-5%minutes}. (For 4 servings, broil pitzas on top and middle racks, swapping rack positions halfway through.) Transfer to a #cutting board{}.

When cool enough to handle, cut pitzas into wedges. Divide between plates.

Place green pepper strips, @chili flakes{1%tsp}, and remaining garlic powder in separate #serving bowls{}. Serve alongside pitzas, with carrots and @buttermilk ranch dressing{1.5%ounce} on the side for dipping.